WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.259
Opa, mas o que quer dizer emocional e racional, Lucas?

2
00:00:03.660 --> 00:00:09.119
E aí, para explicar isso, eu trago o grande pai da transformação organizacional,

3
00:00:09.580 --> 00:00:11.679
que é um cara chamado John Cotter.

4
00:00:12.019 --> 00:00:16.160
John Cotter escreveu um livro chamado Leading Change, ou Liderando a Mudança,

5
00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:31.079
e ele traz para a gente o que quer dizer emocional e racional. so now. Here's a tip, very simple, then I'll explain why it's so important, at least in my opinion.

6
00:00:31.079 --> 00:00:45.000
In a change process of any kind, if it's significant, you have to, in the words of somebody a long time ago, win over the hearts and the minds of people.

7
00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:52.840
And I wonder sometimes if we would simply let that little

8
00:00:53.420 --> 00:00:57.759
phrase ring in our heads all the time,

9
00:00:57.759 --> 00:01:01.159
win over hearts and minds, win over hearts and minds,

10
00:01:01.159 --> 00:01:10.079
if that little change in what's going on in our brains wouldn't make a huge difference

11
00:01:10.079 --> 00:01:17.680
in how we deal with people during a change process and the results we get.

12
00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:51.640
Now let me back up. When we studied successful change projects of any kind again, reorganizations, cultural change, new strategy implementations, doesn't matter what the content is, what we found is that small percentage that were particularly effective, they really did work much more than average, not just on trying

13
00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:59.019
to get people to think differently, which in turn would change their behavior, but to

14
00:01:59.019 --> 00:02:07.000
get people to feel differently, which in turn would change their behavior.

15
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.680
In a typical change effort that I've seen over the years, if you could somehow do an

16
00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:19.340
analysis on those dimensions, the effort to change thinking, the effort to change feeling,

17
00:02:19.340 --> 00:02:29.060
I wouldn't be surprised if on average you found it was 90-10 or at best 80-20 with the 90 and the

18
00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:30.620
80 being on the think part.

19
00:02:30.620 --> 00:02:38.900
I once did an analysis in response to an interviewer about MBA programs and the one that I know

20
00:02:38.900 --> 00:02:49.199
the best and it's even more frightening. About 95% of the program is a work on the mind to change your thinking, and maybe, maybe

21
00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:56.479
5% is on a work on the feelings to change your behavior.

22
00:02:56.479 --> 00:03:03.740
They learn about, they've been taught about, they've been role modeled about the thinking

23
00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:05.000
part.

24
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:06.000
And more and more, of course,

25
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:08.000
that's what's coming into our organizations.

26
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.000
People train that way.

27
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
So what?

28
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.000
If you go back and study the way the brain has been constructed,

29
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:20.000
if you talk to neurologists,

30
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:31.740
what they tell you is that for whatever reasons, historically, you've got two pieces, this more emotional piece and this thinking piece.

31
00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:39.719
And the more emotional piece has a longer history than the thinking side.

32
00:03:39.719 --> 00:03:49.319
And it is more tightly connected in a funny way to those nerves that change and regulate our behavior.

33
00:03:51.120 --> 00:03:54.199
And if you wanna make somebody change

34
00:03:54.199 --> 00:03:57.560
to a significant degree, not just a small degree,

35
00:03:57.560 --> 00:03:59.960
that's the more powerful lever.

36
00:04:01.699 --> 00:04:03.939
And in the most successful cases of change

37
00:04:03.939 --> 00:04:17.680
that we've studied, and you do that little percentage comparison, it's more like they work 60% on the heart side and 40% on the mind side.

38
00:04:17.819 --> 00:04:22.699
It's not 80-20, but it's not even 50-50.

39
00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:25.959
How do they do it?

40
00:04:26.339 --> 00:04:27.240
Hundreds of ways.

41
00:04:29.740 --> 00:04:32.199
I can't think of any, somebody says to me.

42
00:04:32.379 --> 00:04:33.019
No, you can.

43
00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:34.360
It's natural.

44
00:04:34.860 --> 00:04:35.779
It's the way you're built.

45
00:04:36.439 --> 00:04:38.060
You just let it come out.

46
00:04:38.639 --> 00:04:42.379
There are thousands of ways that you can create experiences.

47
00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:45.959
So much role modeling is just that.

48
00:04:45.959 --> 00:04:47.839
It's not, people aren't taking notes.

49
00:04:47.839 --> 00:04:50.339
He did such and such.

50
00:04:50.339 --> 00:04:54.620
There's a direct kind of emotion to emotion connection

51
00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:57.259
that helps you learn something,

52
00:04:57.259 --> 00:04:59.319
changes your feelings about something,

53
00:04:59.319 --> 00:05:01.500
and changes your behavior.

54
00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:10.199
There are hundreds of ways that you can create experiences, that you can feed even data in

55
00:05:10.199 --> 00:05:17.620
a way that doesn't just hit the thinking part but the feeling part.

56
00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:19.439
Get the behavior change.

57
00:05:19.439 --> 00:05:23.120
Make the overall change process work.

58
00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:42.199
Go back to the tip. In your little brain, the more that you can have that voice reminding you, you've got E aí, traduzindo como o próprio Cotter traz para a gente,

59
00:05:42.199 --> 00:05:48.600
Hearts and Minds, no livro dele, a tradução é em liderança e gestão.

60
00:05:49.079 --> 00:05:59.819
Liderança é a capacidade de gerar movimento e fazer a transformação acontecer e gestão é a capacidade de maximizar os resultados.

61
00:05:59.819 --> 00:06:15.319
A minha definição de liderança é que liderança é gerar intencionalidade genuína de ação rumo a um propósito, enquanto gestão é atingir resultados acima da média com recursos limitados.
